{"cursor":"10086","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA ship's 'displacement' or 'displacement tonnage' is the weight of the water\nthat a ship displaces when it is floating; the term is defined ordinarily such\nthat the ship's fuel tanks are full and all stores are aboard. The term is\napplied usually to naval vessels. Displacement is the actual weight of the\nship, since a floating body displaces its own weight in water (Archimedes'\nprinciple). Dear and Kemp, 2006, p.588 George, 2005,\np. 68. Another way of thinking about displacement is the weight of the\nwater that would spill out of a completely filled container were the ship\nplaced into it.\n\nA number of synonymous terms exist for this maximum weight, such as 'loaded\ndisplacement', 'full load displacement' and 'designated displacement'. Turpin and McEwen, 1980. As a measurement of weight,\ndisplacement should not be confused with similarly named measurements of volume\nor capacity such as net tonnage, gross tonnage, or deadweight tonnage.\n\nThe density (weight per unit of volume) of water can vary. For example, the\naverage density of seawater at the surface of the ocean is 1025 kg/mÂ³\n(10.25 lb/ga, 8.55 lb/US gallon); fresh water on the other hand has a\ndensity of about 1000 kg/mÂ³ (10.00 lb/ga, 8.35 lb/US gallon). Consider a 100-ton ship passing from a saltwater sea into a\nfreshwater river. It always displaces exactly 100 tons of water, but it has to\ndisplace a greater volume of fresh water to amount to 100 tons. Therefore it\nwould sit slightly lower in the water in the freshwater river than it would in\nthe saltwater sea.\n\nIt can be useful to know a ship's displacement when it is unloaded or loaded\npartially. Terms for these measurements include 'light displacement', 'standard\ndisplacement', and 'normal displacement'. These terms are defined below.\n","linknr":241,"url":"Displacement_(ship)","recorded":1375087021,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Displacement_(ship)&action=edit","/